The tutorial I chose to complete is the official PyTorch tutorial titled Deep Learning with PyTorch: A 60 Minute Blitz [1]. The tutorial consists of 4 separate mini-tutorials, with the ultimate goal being to get to know PyTorch’s Tensor library. As well to get an overview of neural networks by training a small neural network for image classification. The PyTorch website offers a few different ways to complete the tutorial. In the Training a Classifier section of the tutorial, we are able to put together everything we did in the previous sections [6]. The first step of which is to grab a dataset of images and transform them into tensors that can be fed into the neural network. After which the
class from the previous section is converted to have 3-channel images. Similar to the previous sections we also then defined a loss function, as well as an optimizer.

We then use a for loop to iterate through the dataset. Inside this for loop we put together the steps we have discussed previously. Namely, we zero the parameter gradients, then pass the data through forward propagation, backward propagation, optimize, and repeat. We then save the model and test it to see how accurate it is in total, and then also analyze how accurate it was by category.

Screenshot of the results testing the model from the Jupyter notebook. The accuracy over 10,0000 images was 54%. While the most accurate category was car with an accuracy of 75.8%, and the least accurate category was cat with an accuracy of 27.8%.

This activity was a crucial step in my understanding how aspects of our project will function. PyTorch is a completely new framework for me, and getting some first hand experience with it really helped me understand some concepts, which up until now have been extremely nebulous to me. In the project portal PyTorch was listed as something we were required to get familiar with, and I see why. The framework provides the tools to handle complicated calculations, and in a way provides a bit of a roadmap for what we need to build our model. The PyTorch website also has many more tutorials, as well as thorough documentation which will benefit our project in the long run.
